Distribution

The boxplot shows the distribution of the data from individual YOTs and skewness through displaying the data quartiles. The black line indicates the median and the orange line the mean. Dots placed past the line edges indicate outliers, data points that differs significantly from other observations (two standard deviations above the average). A more detailed explanation of boxplots can be found here. For example, looking at London, the boxplot indicates a range of data points between 1.5 to 7 (or to 9, taking into account the outlier data point). The left line shows the range of values up to the 25th percentile, the box shows that range of values between the 25th and the 75th percentile and the right line, data points over the 75th percentile. In this case the median is roughly the same as the mean, which indicates the data is normally distributed. An outlier is observed at 9, indicating this is a very high value compared to the rest of the data points in London.
